<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Site Control:Knowing the Battlefield<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.54)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=8494'>Ty "Dark Maiden" Hansen</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=8494&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> January 15, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Knowing the Battlefield<br>
<br>
	One of the lessons learned from the history of war is the advantage of terrain.  Vietnam taught the U.S. it needed to be better prepared for jungle and guerrilla warfare.  Desert Storm saw flat desert landscape and different rates of cooling made tanks easy targets for infrared smart-bombs.  Extensive knowledge about the ground one is fighting on is one of the largest advantages a fighting force can have.  With this in mind, the Adventure Path for the Lord of the Rings Trading Card Game will determine how effective both your Fellowship and Shadow forces will be.<br>
	There are three main points this article will focus on: methods of site control, combat effectiveness, and should one choose sites more with Fellowship or Shadow in mind.  These strategy factors, along with your choices of Fellowship, Shadow, and the combination you choose will give one the edge in winning each battle, which ultimately leads to winning the war.<br>
<br>
Methods of Site Control:<br>
<br>
	I cannot overemphasize the importance of being able to choose the battlefield.  Not knowing where your fellowship will move next turn or where your minions will be deploying to are unneeded risks.  The first choice is to always go second, or in other words, stay one step behind.  One would assume this lets you play all your sites(except site 1).  I reject this option for two reasons: forced marches and site-control cards.  If your opponent pushes on just once, you will be forced to twice or they will reach site 9 first.  Putting yourself in the 2 sites behind position limits options and unless you push on enough, forces you to have to stop your opponent.  More important are cards that give a player site control: Pathfinder, Thror&#39;s Map, and Ulaire Nelya.  These cards allow one to go first, second, or however it may turn out, but in any case let you play your sites.  These cards allow you to choose the ground you will be fighting on, on both sides of the coin.  Possible scenarios include: if you went first and pushed on through their site 2 to their site 3, when they move to site 3, dropping Ulaire Nelya, pulling out the Ford of Bruinen and dropping a second fierce Nazgul for 1 or nothing.  When you move to site 4, using Pathfinder or the Map to make sure it isn&#39;t underground to avoid a cheeper Moria Troll, or when you move first to site 7, using either of the Fellowship cards to make sure your allies don&#39;t get discarded if you need them, or if you rely on archery, that the archery phase doesn&#39;t get skipped.  If you have chosen your sites with care, whether it be to hinder your opponent or help your Fellowship, I would think it&#39;s worth it to make sure they get into play in a way that won&#39;t put you behind.  You will always have a hobbit; Frodo hopefully normally doesn&#39;t fight so you can exert him.  And if you don&#39;t have a ranger in your deck to use Pathfinder, and don&#39;t have site control, moving to the Silverlode Banks is going to hurt a lot.  To sum up, I suggest using at least 1, if not all three methods of site control, the Map, Pathfinder and Ulaire Nelya.   That way you know what is coming and can better prepare yourself.  I devote 3-4 Fellowship cards to site control, more if playing a deck more than 70 cards.   Thror&#39;s Map is the best.  Although it costs exertion, you don&#39;t have to keep it in your hand and can use it repeatedly.  This is a more efficient way and the costs are acceptable.  Pathfinder is a one-shot deal, but it is a common card, so might be new players only choice.  Ulaire Nelya is a strength 10, fierce, no roaming cost minion that can slide into any Shadow strategy easily.  His added benefit is he negates your opponents Fellowship site control attempts.  Employing these methods should result in site control, even if you are ahead or behind.  Planning for and choosing the battlefield usually results in victory<br>
<br>
Combat Effectiveness:<br>
<br>
	One wouldn&#39;t want tanks in a rocky, mountainous area or a swampy, wet landscape either.  If you don&#39;t know the terrain, how can you choose the weapons?  One might have 4 Moria Trolls in the deck, but if site 5 is the only one that hits the table that is underground, you will pay an extra 3 twilight per troll everywhere else regardless of how many Keywards you have.  Why pay more  when you can have them cheaper at two more sites?!  Many sites help a particular minion, i.e. Uruk-hai at the Slopes of Amon Hen, but if your opponent uses the Map at site 8, that could mean one or two less last-ditch-effort-hobbit-hunters you get out, illustrating how opponent site control can folly your expected combat benefits.  Having site control will grant your troops increased effectiveness, which in turn will win you the game.  Don&#39;t allow your archers to be overlooked at site 7, don&#39;t let them get out a -5 Nazgul at site 3.  Basically, don&#39;t allow them to use their combat strategy and be much more assured of yours with your sites on the table.<br>
<br>
Sites Should Benefit Your Shadow<br>
<br>
	One can be sure of very few things in this game, but you will move at least one site a turn.  Period.  Since that is the case, your Fellowship has to be prepared to deal with that and hopefully all Shadow strategies that attack you on a one-move basis.  Thus, if your minions can slow your opponent down to one site a turn, if you went first, you win the game, or if you went second, you have your destiny in your own hands at site 8, whether to push to 9 or try and stop them.  I worry about trying a strategy that races ahead, because you cannot predict what your opponent will throw at you.  If your racing fails, will you be able to slow them down or survive a longer, sustained assault.<br>
	If you can reduce the game to a one move game, your site control will be much more effective.  And how do you do this?  With site control!!  If you choose your sites with the most benefits to your minions and get them into play, it should be enough to slow them down.  Cheaper Uruk Messengers get a boost from the Pass of Caradhras and a draw-deck weather condition.  The one-time -2 for a Moria Orc will make them reconsider the usual pushing from site 5-6, which you can have in play even if you&#39;re already there ahead of them.<br>
	What if they are playing the same minions as you are, won&#39;t they get more boost than if you played Fellowship friendly sites, you ask?  To this I answer, your deck should be most prepared to deal with itself.  What I mean by this is that your Fellowship should be be prepare to fight the Shadow you are playing.  Hence if you like Nazgul, play Arwen and Legolas.  But this is another topic for another day.  One should play sites that benefit your Shadow to slow down racers, make the game a one-move game, and then refer to the two paragraphs above about what that leads to.  Finally, if they do race on ahead, you want to be able to hope your sites get out with the normal play, and then you&#39;ll want evil sites rather than not.<br>
<br>
A Sample Choice<br>
<br>
	We will assume you are playing an elf/Nazgul deck, starting Arwen and either Legolas.  Elves are a good way to protect against your opponent&#39;s Nazgul, should he be playing the same Shadow and your Nazgul should slow the game to one site with their fierceness and enough vitality.<br>
	[1] Prancing Pony- to get out Aragorn to heal Arwen and provide another ranger<br>
	[2] Bree Streets- make all your Nazgul have no roaming cost ever!  Better than Weatherhills because it benefits your opponent&#39;s Shadow less with a lower shadow number unless he&#39;s playing Nazgul.  Better than Weathertop because most Nazgul are fierce, and a lower shadow number for opponent playing Sauron or Uruk-hai.<br>
	[3] Ford of Bruinen- Simple, your opponent shouldn&#39;t push to it first turn because of -5 to first Nazgul.<br>
	[4] Most difficult choice.  These don&#39;t benefit your Nazgul really, so pick the best one for your Fellowship.  I say Pass of Caradhras.  Non-underground slows Trolls, don&#39;t want to exert Frodo at the Moria Lake so I can do it to use Thror&#39;s Map.  If they are playing Uruk-hai, at least it&#39;s 1 less twilight.  Other choice would be Mithril Mine, so that you can get Nazgul swords if you discarded them, but I fear the Trolls.  The others don&#39;t benefit your Nazgul, so pick the best one for your Fellowship.<br>
	[5] The Bridge, no other choice, so don&#39;t waste your Pathfinder.<br>
	[6] Galadriel&#39;s Glade-  Once again, none really benefit Nazgul so pick the friendliest.  You have elves, so maybe you want to see their hand next turn.<br>
	[7] Silverlode Banks- You start with a ranger, they may not have one by then.  Allies aren&#39;t that great against the Nazgul, so you don&#39;t have to take them out(things like Their Power is in Terror will)  Your elves are archers hopefully, so don&#39;t skip the phase in the Wilderland.<br>
	[8] Pillars of the Kings or Anduin Banks- Either one.  The Pillars helps your Fellowship if they stop at 8 and you need to push through 8 to win, by not giving their shadow an advantage.  The Banks punishes large parties which can be a good block against Nazgul, so I&#39;d probably pick it. <br>
	[9] Emyn Muil or Summit of Amon Hen-  One helps your few non-fierce Nazgul be fierce and has 1 more twilight.  The Summit allows you to get more cards if you&#39;re playing more of a burden style Nazgul deck.  Don&#39;t forget your Fellowship, which if you have site control cards can give you the easy win by not allowing them to stop you.  Hence I&#39;d choose the Summit which best balances your win/stop them strategies.<br>
<br>
Last Sum Up:<br>
<br>
	I will devote as many cards as it takes to achieve site control because one thing you can be sure of then is the ground you&#39;re fighting on.  Thror&#39;s Map is the best for this, along with Pathfinder and Ulaire Nelya for support.  One cannot plan for everything, but only for as much as can be certain.  There is an Adventure Path and that you will certainly travel along it.  I believe one should know what that future will bring and be better prepared for it.  It may prove the edge that wins you the game. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=3140&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
